The reaction produces hydrogen gas:

\[
\text{Mg(s)} + 2\;\text{HCl(aq)} \rightarrow \text{MgCl}_2\text{(aq)} + \text{H}_2\text{(g)}
\]

Moles of Mg:

\[
n_{\text{Mg}}=\frac{15\;\text{g}}{24.305\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}=0.617\;\text{mol}
\]

From the stoichiometry, \(n_{\text{H}_2}=n_{\text{Mg}}=0.617\;\text{mol}\).

The volume of the produced gas at \(T=298.15\;\text{K}\) and \(P=1.0\;\text{atm}\) (ideal gas) is

\[
V = \frac{nRT}{P}=0.617\;\text{mol}\times\frac{0.082057\;\text{L·atm mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}\times298.15\;\text{K}}{1.0\;\text{atm}}
      = 15.1\;\text{L}
\]

The work done by the system (expansion work) at constant external pressure is

\[
w = -P\Delta V = -(1.0\;\text{atm})(15.1\;\text{L}) = -15.1\;\text{L·atm}
\]

Converting to joules (\(1\;\text{L·atm}=101.325\;\text{J}\)):

\[
w = -15.1\;\text{L·atm}\times101.325\;\frac{\text{J}}{\text{L·atm}}
    = -1.53\times10^{3}\;\text{J}= -1.53\;\text{kJ}
\]

\[
\boxed{-1.53}\ \text{kJ}
\]

The reversible isothermal work for an ideal gas is  

\[
w_{\text{rev}}=-nRT\ln\frac{V_{2}}{V_{1}}
            =-nRT\ln\frac{P_{1}}{P_{2}}
\]

The amount of methane is  

\[
n=\frac{4.50\;\text{g}}{M_{\mathrm{CH_4}}}
  =\frac{4.50}{16.04}\;\text{mol}=0.2805\;\text{mol}
\]

From the ideal‑gas equation for the initial state  

\[
P_{1}=\frac{nRT}{V_{1}}
     =\frac{(0.2805)(8.314\;\text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1})(310\;\text{K})}
            {12.7\times10^{-3}\;\text{m}^{3}}
     =5.69\times10^{4}\;\text{Pa}=0.562\;\text{atm}
\]

The gas expands reversibly until it reaches the external pressure  
\(P_{2}=1.00\;\text{atm}\).  Hence  

\[
w_{\text{rev}}=-nRT\ln\frac{P_{1}}{P_{2}}
              =-(0.2805)(8.314)(310)\,\ln\!\left(\frac{0.562}{1.00}\right)
              =-4.2\times10^{2}\;\text{J}
\]

\[
\boxed{-4.2\times10^{2}}\ \text{J}
\]

The entropy change for vaporisation at the normal boiling point is obtained from  

\[
\Delta S_{\text{vap}}=\frac{\Delta H_{\text{vap}}}{T_{\text{b}}}
\]

\[
\Delta H_{\text{vap}} = 29.4\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}= 2.94\times10^{4}\;\text{J mol}^{-1},
\qquad 
T_{\text{b}} = 334.88\;\text{K}
\]

\[
\Delta S_{\text{vap}} = \frac{2.94\times10^{4}\;\text{J mol}^{-1}}{334.88\;\text{K}}
          \approx 8.78\times10^{1}\;\text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{87.8}\ \text{J K}^{-1}\text{ mol}^{-1}
\]

The total pressure is obtained from the ideal‑gas equation  

\[
P=\frac{nRT}{V},
\]

where  

* total amount of gas \(n = n_{\mathrm{H_2}}+n_{\mathrm{N_2}} = 2.0\;\text{mol}+1.0\;\text{mol}=3.0\;\text{mol}\);
* volume \(V = 22.4\;\text{dm}^3 = 22.4\;\text{L}\);
* temperature \(T = 273.15\;\text{K}\);
* gas constant \(R = 0.082057\;\text{L·atm·K}^{-1}\text{·mol}^{-1}\).

\[
\begin{aligned}
P &= \frac{(3.0\;\text{mol})(0.082057\;\text{L·atm·K}^{-1}\text{·mol}^{-1})(273.15\;\text{K})}{22.4\;\text{L}}\\[4pt]
  &= \frac{3.0 \times 22.414\;\text{L·atm·mol}^{-1}}{22.4\;\text{L}}\\[4pt]
  &= \frac{67.242\;\text{L·atm}}{22.4\;\text{L}}\\[4pt]
  &= 3.0\;\text{atm}.
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\boxed{3.0}\ \text{atm}
\]

The molar heat capacity at constant pressure is obtained from  

\[
C_{p,m}= \frac{q}{n\,\Delta T}
       = \frac{229\ \text{J}}{(3.0\ \text{mol})(2.55\ \text{K})}
       = \frac{229}{7.65}\ \text{J\,K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}
       \approx 30\ \text{J\,K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1}.
\]

\[
\boxed{30}\ \text{J K}^{-1}\text{ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\Delta G = RT\ln\frac{P_{2}}{P_{1}}
        = (8.314\;\text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1})(298\;\text{K})\ln\frac{100\;\text{atm}}{1\;\text{atm}}
        \approx 1.14\times10^{4}\;\text{J mol}^{-1}
        = 11.4\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{11.4}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

The entropy change of the gas can be obtained from a reversible path that connects the same initial and final states:

\[
\Delta S = nC_{V,m}\ln\!\frac{T_f}{T_i}+nR\ln\!\frac{V_f}{V_i}
\]

---

**1.  Initial state**

\[
\begin{aligned}
n &= 2.0\ \text{mol}\\
T_i &= 298.15\ \text{K}\\
P_i &= 10\ \text{atm}=10(101325)\ \text{Pa}=1.01325\times10^{6}\ \text{Pa}\\[2mm]
V_i &=\frac{nRT_i}{P_i}
      =\frac{(2.0)(8.314\ \text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1})(298.15\ \text{K})}
            {1.01325\times10^{6}\ \text{Pa}}
      =4.894\times10^{-3}\ \text{m}^{3}
\end{aligned}
\]

---

**2.  Work done (adiabatic expansion against a constant external pressure)**  

Cross‑sectional area \(A = 10.0\ \text{cm}^2 = 1.0\times10^{-3}\ \text{m}^2\)  

Piston displacement \(\Delta x = 20\ \text{cm}=0.20\ \text{m}\)

\[
\Delta V = A\Delta x = 2.0\times10^{-4}\ \text{m}^{3}
\]

External pressure \(P_{\text{ext}} = 1.0\ \text{atm}=1.01325\times10^{5}\ \text{Pa}\)

\[
w = -P_{\text{ext}}\Delta V = -(1.01325\times10^{5})(2.0\times10^{-4})
    = -20.27\ \text{J}
\]

Because the process is adiabatic, \(q=0\) and \(\Delta U = w\).

---

**3.  Final temperature**

\[
\Delta U = nC_{V,m}(T_f-T_i) = -20.27\ \text{J}
\]

\[
T_f = T_i + \frac{\Delta U}{nC_{V,m}}
     = 298.15\ \text{K} - \frac{20.27\ \text{J}}{(2.0)(28.8\ \text{J K}^{-1}\text{mol}^{-1})}
     = 2.98\times10^{2}\ \text{K}= 297.80\ \text{K}
\]

---

**4.  Final volume**

\[
V_f = V_i + \Delta V = 4.894\times10^{-3} + 2.0\times10^{-4}
      = 5.094\times10^{-3}\ \text{m}^{3}
\]

---

**5.  Entropy change**

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta S &= nC_{V,m}\ln\!\frac{T_f}{T_i}+nR\ln\!\frac{V_f}{V_i}\\[2mm]
        &= (2.0)(28.8)\ln\!\frac{297.80}{298.15}
           +(2.0)(8.314)\ln\!\frac{5.094\times10^{-3}}{4.894\times10^{-3}}\\[2mm]
        &= 57.6\,( -1.18\times10^{-3}) + 16.628\,(0.0400)\\[2mm]
        &= -0.068\ \text{J K}^{-1} + 0.666\ \text{J K}^{-1}\\[2mm]
        &= 0.60\ \text{J K}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\boxed{0.60}\ \text{J K}^{-1}
\]

The mass loss through a small hole into vacuum is described by the Hertz–Knudsen (Langmuir) equation  

\[
\dot m = \frac{PA}{\sqrt{2\pi RT/M}}
\]

where  

* \( \dot m\) – mass‑loss rate (kg s\(^{-1}\))  
* \(P\) – vapour pressure (Pa)  
* \(A\) – area of the hole (m\(^2\))  
* \(R = 8.314\;\text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1}\)  
* \(T\) – absolute temperature (K)  
* \(M\) – molar mass of Cs (\(M = 132.905\;\text{g mol}^{-1}=0.132905\;\text{kg mol}^{-1}\))

---

### 1.  Mass‑loss rate  

\[
\Delta m = 385\;\text{mg}=0.385\;\text{g}=3.85\times10^{-4}\;\text{kg}
\]

\[
\dot m = \frac{\Delta m}{\Delta t}= \frac{3.85\times10^{-4}\;\text{kg}}{100\;\text{s}}
          = 3.85\times10^{-6}\;\text{kg s}^{-1}
\]

### 2.  Hole area  

Diameter \(d = 0.50\;\text{mm}=5.0\times10^{-4}\;\text{m}\)

\[
A = \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}
   = \pi (2.5\times10^{-4}\;\text{m})^{2}
   = 1.96\times10^{-7}\;\text{m}^{2}
\]

### 3.  Evaluate the kinetic factor  

\[
\sqrt{\frac{2\pi RT}{M}}
   = \sqrt{\frac{2\pi (8.314)(500)}{0.132905}}
   = \sqrt{1.966\times10^{5}}
   \approx 4.44\times10^{2}\;\text{m s}^{-1}
\]

### 4.  Solve for the vapour pressure  

\[
P = \frac{\dot m\,\sqrt{2\pi RT/M}}{A}
   = \frac{(3.85\times10^{-6})(4.44\times10^{2})}
          {1.96\times10^{-7}}
   \approx 8.7\times10^{3}\;\text{Pa}
\]

\[
\boxed{8.7}\ \text{kPa}
\]

question:
$$
\text {Calculate the energy of a photon for a wavelength of } 100 \mathrm{pm} \text { (about one atomic diameter). }
$$

llm_output:
The energy of one photon is  

\[
E_{\text{ph}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
          =\frac{(6.626\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})(3.00\times10^{8}\,\text{m/s})}
                 {1.06\times10^{-6}\,\text{m}}
          \approx 1.88\times10^{-19}\,\text{J}.
\]

The pulse energy is \(E_{\text{pulse}} = 2.00\;\text{mJ}=2.00\times10^{-3}\,\text{J}\).

\[
N=\frac{E_{\text{pulse}}}{E_{\text{ph}}}
  =\frac{2.00\times10^{-3}}{1.88\times10^{-19}}
  \approx 1.07\times10^{16}\;\text{photons}.
\]

\[
\boxed{1.07}\times10^{16}\ \text{photons}
\]

The spacing between successive rotational lines is  

\[
\Delta \nu = 6.26\times10^{11}\;\text{Hz}=2B\;\Longrightarrow\;B=3.13\times10^{11}\;\text{Hz}
\]

For a rigid rotor  

\[
B=\frac{h}{8\pi^{2}I}\qquad\Longrightarrow\qquad 
I=\frac{h}{8\pi^{2}B}
\]

\[
I=\frac{6.62607015\times10^{-34}\ \text{J·s}}
        {8\pi^{2}(3.13\times10^{11}\ \text{s}^{-1})}
  =2.68\times10^{-47}\ \text{kg·m}^{2}
\]

The reduced mass of \(\mathrm{H}^{35}\mathrm{Cl}\) is  

\[
\mu=\frac{m_{\mathrm H}\,m_{\mathrm{Cl}}}{m_{\mathrm H}+ \;m_{\mathrm{Cl}}
   =\frac{(1.007825\ \text{u})(34.968852\ \text{u})}
          {1.007825\ \text{u}+34.968852\ \text{u}}
   =0.9795\ \text{u}
   =0.9795(1.6605390666\times10^{-27})\ \text{kg}
   =1.63\times10^{-27}\ \text{kg}
\]

The bond length \(r\) follows from \(I=\mu r^{2}\):

\[
r=\sqrt{\frac{I}{\mu}}
  =\sqrt{\frac{2.68\times10^{-47}}{1.63\times10^{-27}}}
  =1.28\times10^{-10}\ \text{m}
  =1.28\times10^{-10}\ \text{m}\times10^{12}\ \frac{\text{pm}}{\text{m}}
  =1.28\times10^{2}\ \text{pm}
\]

\[
\boxed{128}\ \text{pm}
\]

The photon energy required to promote an electron across the band gap is  

\[
E=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
\]

Using the convenient constant \(hc = 1240\;\text{eV·nm}\) and the threshold wavelength \(\lambda = 350\;\text{nm}\),

\[
E = \frac{1240\;\text{eV·nm}}{350\;\text{nm}}
   = 3.542857\;\text{eV}
   \approx 3.54\;\text{eV}.
\]

\[
\boxed{3.54}\ \text{eV}
\]

The calorimeter heat capacity is obtained from the benzoic‑acid calibration:

\[
\begin{aligned}
n_{\text{BA}} &=\frac{0.825\;\text{g}}{122.12\;\text{g mol}^{-1}} = 6.76\times10^{-3}\;\text{mol}\\[2pt]
q_{\text{BA}} &= n_{\text{BA}}\;(-3251\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}) = -21.97\;\text{kJ}\\[2pt]
C_{\text{cal}} &=\frac{|q_{\text{BA}}|}{\Delta T}= \frac{21.97\;\text{kJ}}{1.940\;\text{K}}
               = 11.33\;\text{kJ K}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

For D‑ribose:

\[
\begin{aligned}
n_{\text{rib}} &=\frac{0.727\;\text{g}}{150.13\;\text{g mol}^{-1}} = 4.84\times10^{-3}\;\text{mol}\\[2pt]
q_{\text{rib}} &= C_{\text{cal}}\;\Delta T = 11.33\;\text{kJ K}^{-1}\times0.910\;\text{K}
                = 10.31\;\text{kJ}\\[2pt]
\Delta U_{\text{comb}}(\text{rib}) &= -\frac{q_{\text{rib}}}{n_{\text{rib}}}
                                    = -\frac{10.31\;\text{kJ}}{4.84\times10^{-3}\;\text{mol}}
                                    = -2.13\times10^{3}\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Because the combustion reaction  

\[
\mathrm{C_5H_{10}O_5(s)} + 5\,\mathrm{O_2(g)} \rightarrow 5\,\mathrm{CO_2(g)} + 5\,\mathrm{H_2O(l)}
\]

has \(\Delta n_{\text{gas}} = 0\), \(\Delta H_{\text{comb}} = \Delta U_{\text{comb}}\).

Using the standard formation enthalpies \(\Delta_f H^\circ(\mathrm{CO_2}) = -393.5\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\) and \(\Delta_f H^\circ(\mathrm{H_2O(l)}) = -285.8\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta_c H^\circ(\text{rib}) &= 5\Delta_f H^\circ(\mathrm{CO_2}) + 5\Delta_f H^\circ(\mathrm{H_2O})
                               - \Delta_f H^\circ(\text{rib})\\
-2129\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1} &= 5(-393.5) + 5(-285.8) - \Delta_f H^\circ(\text{rib})\\
\Delta_f H^\circ(\text{rib}) &= -3396.5 + 2129\\
\Delta_f H^\circ(\text{rib}) &= -1.27\times10^{3}\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\boxed{-1.27\times10^{3}}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

The overall reduction reaction is  

\[
\mathrm{Ce^{4+}+4e^- \longrightarrow Ce(s)}
\]

It can be obtained by adding the two half‑reactions  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{Ce^{4+}+e^- &\longrightarrow Ce^{3+}}\qquad E_1^{\circ}=+1.61\ \text{V}\\
\mathrm{Ce^{3+}+3e^- &\longrightarrow Ce(s)}\qquad E_2^{\circ}=-2.34\ \text{V}
\end{aligned}
\]

Convert each potential to standard Gibbs energy (\(\Delta G^{\circ}=-nFE^{\circ}\)):

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta G_1^{\circ}&=- (1)(F)(+1.61)= -1.61\,F\\[2pt]
\Delta G_2^{\circ}&=- (3)(F)(-2.34)= +7.02\,F
\end{aligned}
\]

Add the Gibbs energies:

\[
\Delta G_{\text{total}}^{\circ}=(-1.61+7.02)F = 5.41\,F
\]

The overall reaction involves \(n_{\text{total}} = 4\) electrons, so the standard potential for the \(\mathrm{Ce^{4+}/Ce}\) couple is

\[
E^{\circ}_{\mathrm{Ce^{4+}/Ce}} = -\frac{\Delta G_{\text{total}}^{\circ}}{n_{\text{total}}F}
= -\frac{5.41\,F}{4F}= -1.35\ \text{V}
\]

\[
\boxed{-1.35}\ \text{V}
\]

The photon energy from the He‑lamp is  

\[
E_{\text{ph}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
          =\frac{(6.62607015\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})(2.99792458\times10^{8}\,\text{m s}^{-1})}
                 {58.4\times10^{-9}\,\text{m}}
          =3.40\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}
          =\frac{3.40\times10^{-18}}{1.602176634\times10^{-19}}\;\text{eV}
          \approx 21.2\;\text{eV}.
\]

The kinetic energy of the emitted electrons is  

\[
K=\frac12 mv^{2}
  =\frac12 (9.10938356\times10^{-31}\,\text{kg})(1.59\times10^{6}\,\text{m s}^{-1})^{2}
  =1.15\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}
  =\frac{1.15\times10^{-18}}{1.602176634\times10^{-19}}\;\text{eV}
  \approx 7.2\;\text{eV}.
\]

The ionization (work) energy of krypton is the difference between the photon energy and the kinetic energy of the electrons:

\[
\phi = E_{\text{ph}}-K \approx 21.2\;\text{eV} - 7.2\;\text{eV}
      \approx 14.1\;\text{eV}.
\]

\[
\boxed{14.1}\ \text{eV}
\]

The Clapeyron relation for the solid–liquid equilibrium is  

\[
\frac{dT}{dP}= \frac{T\Delta V}{\Delta H_{\text{fus}}}
\]

where  

\[
\Delta V = V_{\text{liq}}-V_{\text{ice}},\qquad 
\Delta H_{\text{fus}}\approx 6.01\times10^{3}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}
\]

and \(T\) is taken as the normal melting temperature \(273.15\ \text{K}\).

---

**Molar volumes**

\[
V_{\text{ice}}=\frac{M}{\rho_{\text{ice}}}
          =\frac{18.015\ \text{g mol}^{-1}}{0.92\ \text{g cm}^{-3}}
          =19.58\ \text{cm}^{3}\text{ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
V_{\text{liq}}=\frac{M}{\rho_{\text{liq}}}
          =\frac{18.015\ \text{g mol}^{-1}}{1.00\ \text{g cm}^{-3}}
          =18.015\ \text{cm}^{3}\text{ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\Delta V = 18.015-19.58 = -1.565\ \text{cm}^{3}\text{ mol}^{-1}
        = -1.565\times10^{-6}\ \text{m}^{3}\text{ mol}^{-1}
\]

---

**Slope of the melting curve**

\[
\frac{dT}{dP}= \frac{273.15\ \text{K}\times(-1.565\times10^{-6}\ \text{m}^{3}\text{ mol}^{-1})}
                    {6.01\times10^{3}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}}
            = -7.1\times10^{-8}\ \text{K Pa}^{-1}
\]

---

**Pressure change**

The pressure increase from 1 bar (≈0.1 MPa) to 50 bar is  

\[
\Delta P = (50-1)\,\text{bar}=49\ \text{bar}=4.9\times10^{6}\ \text{Pa}
\]

---

**Melting‑point shift**

\[
\Delta T = \frac{dT}{dP}\,\Delta P
        = (-7.1\times10^{-8}\ \text{K Pa}^{-1})(4.9\times10^{6}\ \text{Pa})
        \approx -0.35\ \text{K}
\]

Thus the melting temperature at 50 bar is  

\[
T_{\text{m}} = 273.15\ \text{K} - 0.35\ \text{K}
             \approx 272.8\ \text{K}
\]

\[
\boxed{272.8}\ \text{K}
\]

The photon energy is  

\[
E_{\text{ph}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}= \frac{1240\;\text{eV·nm}}{305\;\text{nm}}=4.07\;\text{eV}
\]

The work function \(\phi\) of the metal follows from the photoelectric equation  

\[
E_{\text{ph}} = \phi + K_{\max}
\]

\[
\phi = E_{\text{ph}}-K_{\max}=4.07\;\text{eV}-1.77\;\text{eV}=2.30\;\text{eV}
\]

The longest (maximum) wavelength that can just liberate an electron corresponds to a photon whose energy equals the work function (\(K_{\max}=0\)):

\[
\lambda_{\max}= \frac{hc}{\phi}= \frac{1240\;\text{eV·nm}}{2.30\;\text{eV}}
           \approx 5.40\times10^{2}\;\text{nm}
\]

\[
\boxed{540}\ \text{nm}
\]

The energy of one photon of wavelength \( \lambda = 300\ \text{nm}=3.00\times10^{-7}\ \text{m} \) is  

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
   =\frac{(6.626\times10^{-34}\ \text{J·s})(3.00\times10^{8}\ \text{m·s}^{-1})}
          {3.00\times10^{-7}\ \text{m}}
   =6.63\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}.
\]

For one mole of photons we multiply by Avogadro’s number \(N_{\!A}=6.022\times10^{23}\ \text{mol}^{-1}\):

\[
E_{\text{mol}} = E_{\text{photon}}\,N_{\!A}
   = (6.63\times10^{-19}\ \text{J})(6.022\times10^{23}\ \text{mol}^{-1})
   = 3.99\times10^{5}\ \text{J·mol}^{-1}
   \approx 3.99\times10^{2}\ \text{kJ·mol}^{-1}.
\]

Thus the energy of one mole of 300 nm UV photons is essentially the same as a typical single‑bond energy (~\(400\ \text{kJ·mol}^{-1}\)).

\[
\boxed{399}\ \text{kJ·mol}^{-1}
\]

The de Broglie wavelength is  

\[
\lambda=\frac{h}{mv}
      =\frac{6.62607015\times10^{-34}\ \text{J·s}}
             {(9.10938356\times10^{-31}\ \text{kg})\,
              \left(\dfrac{c}{137}\right)}
      =\frac{6.62607015\times10^{-34}}
