      \approx 3.32\times10^{-10}\ \text{m}
      =0.332\ \text{nm}.
\]

\[
\boxed{0.332}\ \text{nm}
\]

The electrostatic force between the α‑particle (charge \(+2e\)) and the gold nucleus (charge \(+79e\)) at a separation \(r\) is given by Coulomb’s law  

\[
F = k\,\frac{|q_1 q_2|}{r^{2}}
   = k\,\frac{(2e)(79e)}{r^{2}}
   = k\,\frac{158\,e^{2}}{r^{2}} .
\]

\[
\begin{aligned}
k &= 8.987551787\times10^{9}\ \text{N·m}^{2}\!\!/\text{C}^{2},\\[4pt]
e &= 1.602176634\times10^{-19}\ \text{C},\\[4pt]
r &= 0.00300\ \text{Å}=0.00300\times10^{-10}\ \text{m}=3.00\times10^{-13}\ \text{m}.
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\begin{aligned}
k e^{2} &= 8.987551787\times10^{9}\times(1.602176634\times10^{-19})^{2}
        = 2.307\times10^{-28}\ \text{N·m}^{2},\\[4pt]
158\,k e^{2} &= 158\times2.307\times10^{-28}
            = 3.645\times10^{-26}\ \text{N·m}^{2},\\[4pt]
r^{2} &= (3.00\times10^{-13})^{2}=9.00\times10^{-26}\ \text{m}^{2}.
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
F = \frac{3.645\times10^{-26}}{9.00\times10^{-26}}
   = 0.405\ \text{N}.
\]

\[
\boxed{0.405}\ \text{N}
\]

The vibrational temperature for a mode with wavenumber \(\tilde\nu = 900\;\text{cm}^{-1}\) is  

\[
\theta = \frac{h c \tilde\nu}{k}
      = \frac{(6.62607015\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})(2.99792458\times10^{10}\,\text{cm·s}^{-1})(900\,\text{cm}^{-1})}
             {1.380649\times10^{-23}\,\text{J·K}^{-1}}
      \approx 1.29\times10^{3}\,\text{K}.
\]

At \(T = 25^{\circ}\text{C}=298.15\;\text{K}\),

\[
\frac{\theta}{e^{\theta/T}-1}
   = \frac{1294\;\text{K}}{e^{1294/298.15}-1}
   \approx \frac{1294}{75.6}
   \approx 17.1 .
\]

Hence the molar internal‑energy contribution of this single vibrational mode is  

\[
