\[
\text{pH}=9\;\Longrightarrow\;\text{pOH}=14-9=5
\]
\[
[\ce{OH^-}] = 10^{-5}\ \text{mol·dm}^{-3}=x
\]

Hence at equilibrium  

\[
[\ce{X^-}] = C-x\approx 0.20-10^{-5}\approx 0.20\ \text{M}
\]
\[
[\ce{HX}] = x = 10^{-5}\ \text{M}
\]
\[
[\ce{OH^-}] = x = 10^{-5}\ \text{M}
\]

The base‑hydrolysis constant is

\[
K_b = \frac{[\ce{HX}][\ce{OH^-}]}{[\ce{X^-}]}
      = \frac{x^{2}}{C-x}
      \approx \frac{(10^{-5})^{2}}{0.20}
      = 5.0\times10^{-10}
\]

For the conjugate acid–base pair  

\[
K_a K_b = K_w = 1.0\times10^{-14}
\]

Thus

\[
K_a = \frac{K_w}{K_b}
     = \frac{1.0\times10^{-14}}{5.0\times10^{-10}}
     = 2.0\times10^{-5}
\]

