**Step 1 – Write the hydro‑lysis reactions of the conjugate bases**

\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{A^-}+ \mathrm{H_2O}&\rightleftharpoons \mathrm{HA}+ \mathrm{OH^-}\qquad K_{b,\;A}= \frac{K_w}{K_{HA}}\\[2mm]
\mathrm{B^-}+ \mathrm{H_2O}&\rightleftharpoons \mathrm{HB}+ \mathrm{OH^-}\qquad K_{b,\;B}= \frac{K_w}{K_{HB}}
\end{aligned}
\]

with \(K_w =1.0\times10^{-14}\) (25 °C).

\[
\begin{aligned}
K_{b,\;A}&=\frac{1.0\times10^{-14}}{1.74\times10^{-7}}
          =5.75\times10^{-8}\\[2mm]
K_{b,\;B}&=\frac{1.0\times10^{-14}}{1.34\times10^{-7}}
          =7.46\times10^{-8}
\end{aligned}
\]

**Step 2 – Set up mass‑balance and equilibrium expressions**

Let  

\[
C_A =0.0600\;\text{M},\qquad C_B =0.0400\;\text{M}
\]

be the initial concentrations of \(\mathrm{A^-}\) and \(\mathrm{B^-}\).

If \(x\) mol L\(^{-1}\) of \(\mathrm{A^-}\) hydrolyse and \(y\) mol L\(^{-1}\) of \(\mathrm{B^-}\) hydrolyse, then  

\[
\begin{aligned}
[\mathrm{A^-}] &= C_A - x, &[\mathrm{HA}] &= x\\
[\mathrm{B^-}] &= C_B - y, &[\mathrm{HB}] &= y\\
[\mathrm{OH^-}] &= x+y\equiv O
\end{aligned}
\]

The equilibrium constants give  

\[
\begin{aligned}
K_{b,\;A}&=\frac{x\,O}{C_A-x}\qquad\Longrightarrow\qquad 
x=\frac{K_{b,\;A}C_A}{O+K_{b,\;A}}\\[4pt]
K_{b,\;B}&=\frac{y\,O}{C_B-y}\qquad\Longrightarrow\qquad 
y=\frac{K_{b,\;B}C_B}{O+K_{b,\;B}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Because \(O=x+y\),

\[
O=\frac{K_{b,\;A}C_A}{O+K_{b,\;A}}+\frac{K_{b,\;B}C_B}{O+K_{b,\;B}}
\tag{1}
\]

**Step 3 – Solve equation (1) for \(O\)**  

Insert the numerical values  

\[
\begin{aligned}
K_{b,\;A}C_A &=5.75\times10^{-8}\times0.0600 =3.45\times10^{-9}\\
K_{b,\;B}C_B &=7.46\times10^{-8}\times0.0400 =2.99\times10^{-9}
\end{aligned}
\]

Equation (1) becomes  

\[
O=\frac{3.45\times10^{-9}}{O+5.75\times10^{-8}}+
   \frac{2.99\times10^{-9}}{O+7.46\times10^{-8}}
\]

Because the expected \(O\) is of the order \(10^{-4}\,\text{M}\) (much larger than the \(K_b\) values), we can solve iteratively.  
Starting with \(O_0=8.0\times10^{-5}\,\text{M}\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
O_1 &=\frac{3.45\times10^{-9}}{8.0\times10^{-5}+5.75\times10^{-8}}
      +\frac{2.99\times10^{-9}}{8.0\times10^{-5}+7.46\times10^{-8}}\\
    &=4.29\times10^{-5}+3.71\times10^{-5}=7.99\times10^{-5}\;\text{M}
\end{aligned}
\]

Repeating once more gives the same value to three significant figures, so  

\[
[\mathrm{OH^-}] = O \approx 8.0\times10^{-5}\;\text{M}
\]

**Step 4 – Convert \([\mathrm{OH^-}]\) to pH**

\[
\begin{aligned}
pOH &= -\log_{10}(8.0\times10^{-5}) = 4.10\\
pH  &= 14.00 - pOH = 14.00 - 4.10 = 9.90
\end{aligned}
\]

---

\[
\boxed{9.90}
