This Ni originated from a \(25.0\;\text{mL}\) aliquot, i.e. half of the original 50 mL solution that contained the dissolved 0.425 g sample. Hence the total Ni in the original solution (and thus in the sample) is twice this amount:

\[
m_{\text{Ni,total}} = 2(0.053\;\text{mg}) = 0.106\;\text{mg}
\]

Finally, the concentration of Ni in the original sample expressed in parts per million (mass of Ni per mass of sample × 10⁶) is

\[
\text{Ni(ppm)} = \frac{0.106\;\text{mg}}{0.425\;\text{g}}\times10^{6}
               = 2.48\times10^{2}\;\text{ppm}
\]

\[
\boxed{2.48\times10^{2}}\ \text{Ni(ppm)}
\]

The absorbances are described by the simultaneous equations  

\[
\begin{cases}
A_{510}= \varepsilon_{\text{Co},510}\,c_{\text{Co}}+\varepsilon_{\text{Ni},510}\,c_{\text{Ni}}\\[2pt]
A_{656}= \varepsilon_{\text{Co},656}\,c_{\text{Co}}+\varepsilon_{\text{Ni},656}\,c_{\text{Ni}}
\end{cases}
\]

with \(l=1\;\text{cm}\).

\[
\begin{aligned}
0.446 &= 36400\,c_{\text{Co}}+5520\,c_{\text{Ni}}\\
0.326 &= 1240\,c_{\text{Co}}+17500\,c_{\text{Ni}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Solving for \(c_{\text{Co}}\) (Cramer's rule):

\[
c_{\text{Co}}=
\frac{0.446(17500)-0.326(5520)}
{36400(17500)-5520(1240)}
=9.54\times10^{-6}\;\text{mol L}^{-1}
\]

The measured solution was prepared by taking a \(25.0\;\text{mL}\) aliquot of the original
\(50.0\;\text{mL}\) stock and diluting it to \(50.0\;\text{mL}\); therefore the cobalt
concentration in the original stock is twice this value:

\[
c_{\text{Co,stock}} = 2(9.54\times10^{-6}) = 1.91\times10^{-5}\;\text{mol L}^{-1}
\]

Moles of Co in the original \(0.425\;\text{g}\) sample (contained in the \(50.0\;\text{mL}\) stock):

\[
n_{\text{Co}} = c_{\text{Co,stock}}\times 0.0500\;\text{L}
               = 1.91\times10^{-5}\times 0.0500
               = 9.54\times10^{-7}\;\text{mol}
\]

Mass of Co (atomic weight \(M_{\text{Co}} = 58.93\;\text{g mol}^{-1}\)):

\[
m_{\text{Co}} = n_{\text{Co}}M_{\text{Co}}
               = 9.54\times10^{-7}\times 58.93
               = 5.62\times10^{-5}\;\text{g}=0.0562\;\text{mg}
\]

Parts‑per‑million (mg Co per kg of sample):

\[
\text{ppm}_{\text{Co}} = \frac{0.0562\;\text{mg}}{0.425\;\text{g}}\times 10^{3}
                       = 1.32\times10^{2}\;\text{ppm}
\]

\[
\boxed{132}\;\text{Co(ppm)}
\]

The titration neutralises the carboxylic‑acid end groups of the PLA chains.  
One polymer chain contains one acidic end group, therefore the moles of KOH used equal the moles of polymer molecules.

\[
\begin{aligned}
n_{\text{KOH}} &= C_{\text{KOH}}\;V_{\text{KOH}} \\
               &= 0.0400\;\text{mol L}^{-1}\times 6.81\times10^{-3}\;\text{L} \\
               &= 2.724\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus  

\[
n_{\text{PLA}} = n_{\text{KOH}} = 2.724\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}
\]

The average molar mass \( \overline{M} \) is the mass of the sample divided by the number of moles of polymer chains:

\[
\overline{M}= \frac{m_{\text{PLA}}}{n_{\text{PLA}}}
            = \frac{0.1619\;\text{g}}{2.724\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}}
            = 5.95\times10^{2}\;\text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{5.95\times10^{2}}\ \text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

The change in Gibbs energy for a liquid at constant temperature is  

\[
\Delta G = \int_{P_1}^{P_2} V_m\,dP \approx V_m\,(P_2-P_1)
\]

where \(V_m\) is the molar volume (treated as constant for an incompressible liquid).

**Molar volume of octane**

\[
\begin{aligned}
M_{\text{octane}} &= 8(12.01)+18(1.008)=114.2\ \text{g mol}^{-1}\\[2mm]
\rho &=0.703\ \text{g cm}^{-3}=0.703\times10^{3}\ \text{kg m}^{-3}\\[2mm]
V_m &=\frac{M}{\rho}= \frac{114.2\ \text{g mol}^{-1}}{0.703\ \text{g cm}^{-3}}
      =162.5\ \text{cm}^{3}\text{ mol}^{-1}=1.625\times10^{-4}\ \text{m}^{3}\text{ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

**Pressure change**

\[
\Delta P = (100-1)\,\text{atm}=99\ \text{atm}=99(1.01325\times10^{5})\ \text{Pa}
        =1.003\times10^{7}\ \text{Pa}
\]

**Change in Gibbs energy**

\[
\Delta G = V_m\,\Delta P
         = (1.625\times10^{-4}\ \text{m}^{3}\text{ mol}^{-1})(1.003\times10^{7}\ \text{Pa})
         \approx 1.63\times10^{3}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}
         = 1.6\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{1.6}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

The photon energy is  

\[
E_{\text{ph}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
          =\frac{(6.626\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})(3.00\times10^{8}\,\text{m s}^{-1})}{100\times10^{-9}\,\text{m}}
          =1.99\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}=12.4\ \text{eV}.
\]

The kinetic energy of the ejected electron is  

\[
K = E_{\text{ph}}-E_{\text{ion}} = 12.4\ \text{eV}-12.0\ \text{eV}=0.41\ \text{eV}
    =0.41(1.602\times10^{-19}\,\text{J})=6.57\times10^{-20}\,\text{J}.
\]

Using \(K=\tfrac12 m_e v^{2}\) with \(m_e=9.109\times10^{-31}\,\text{kg}\),

\[
v=\sqrt{\frac{2K}{m_e}}
  =\sqrt{\frac{2(6.57\times10^{-20})}{9.109\times10^{-31}}}
  =3.8\times10^{5}\ \text{m s}^{-1}.
\]

\[
\boxed{3.8\times10^{5}} \ \text{m s}^{-1}
\]

The combustion of methane written for gaseous reactants is  

\[
\ce{CH4(g) + 2 O2(g) -> CO2(g) + 2 H2O(g)}\qquad \Delta H^\circ = -890.8\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

When the reactants are liquids we must first vaporise them:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\ce{CH4(l) &-> CH4(g)} &\Delta H_{\text{vap}}(\ce{CH4}) &= +8.2\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\\[2pt]
2\,\ce{O2(l) &-> 2 O2(g)} &2\Delta H_{\text{vap}}(\ce{O2}) &= 2\times 6.8 = +13.6\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus the enthalpy change for the overall reaction with liquid reactants is  

\[
\Delta H_{\text{rxn}} = \Delta H_{\text{comb}}^{\text{(g)}} 
+ \Delta H_{\text{vap}}(\ce{CH4}) + 2\Delta H_{\text{vap(\ce{O2})
\]

\[
\Delta H_{\text{rxn}} = -890.8\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1} + 8.2\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1} + 13.6\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
= -869.0\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{-869\ \text{kJ}}
\]
